Published Brumbach family genealogy research<ref>Genealogy of the Brumbach families, Gaius Marcus Brumbach, Frederick H Hitchcock Genealogical Publisher, New York, 1913, p 273</ref> contains a narrative of Hans Jacob's arrival in America:

:According to tradition among some of his Virginia descendants, he and a young woman, his fellow passenger across the Atlantic, served ''Joseph Strickler'' for seven years.

The researcher further explains that the laws about this kind of indenture varied, and the term could have been shorter.  While unable to identify the "young woman", the narrative continues:

:After their service to Strickler ended they married and had one son, ''George''.  After the death of this wife Jacob Roadcap married a widow ''Good'' (first name unknown), and had by her one child, ''Peter''.  

A different version of their marriage is found in an account of the trip across the Atlantic<ref>A history of the Goshenhoppen Reformed charge, Montgomery County, Pennsylvania (1727-1819), William John Hinke, Lancaster [Press of the New era printing company], 1920, p 101, https://archive.org/details/historyofgoshen00hink/page/100/mode/2up</ref>, which references "a pamphlet which Ludwig Weber, one of the emigrants, who returned to Zurich from Holland, wrote and published at Zurich in 1735 as a warning to later venturesome spirits<ref>The title page of this pamphlet reads: ''Der Hinckende Bott von Carolina Oder Ludivig Webers von Walliselen Beschreibung seiner Reitse von Zurich gen Rotterdam, mit derjenigen Gesellschaft welch neulich aus dem Schweizerland nach Carolinam zu Ziehen gedachte'', Zurich, MDCCXXXV, pp. 32. Only known copy in the city library at Zurich</ref>.  This account lists "Jacob Rathgeb and Barbara Haller" among four couples who were married by a Reformed minister in Neuwied in October 1734.  They arrived in Philadelphia 29 May 1735.

Adding names to the Brumbach information, and parsing the specific words used, the researcher's "one son" phrasing places John George and all of Hans Jacob's daughters with Barbara Haller, and he had only Peter ("one child") with Anna Naef.  A researcher must decide whether the Brumbach narrative can be trusted, because trusting it would significantly alter the perceived birth years of the children.

Given the era, it would be surprising for a couple married in 1734 to avoid childbirth until (for example) 1740.  However, considering that the age of orphans would be younger than 21, the children listed in the guardian bond (and certainly Peter) would have been born after 1740, and John George's absence from the list suggests that he is the eldest, and possibly born 1740.  It is also possible that the timing of the guardian bond was prompted by John George reaching majority age.

